post_text:
Our first day of school went very smoothly overall yesterday. It was great to have the kids back into the building and they very quickly adapted to the new procedures, schedules, and requirements. How our students and staff executed our plan so far has been nothing short of amazing.

The one wrinkle we had was with water. We are not allowed to have water fountain use during this time. We have ordered a few touchless water bottle fillers but they have not arrived as of yet and may be a short time wait as there is a nationwide request for them.

We will have cases of water bottles on hand for the time being but we ask that you send water with your students in the morning as supplies run out quickly. We also will gladly accept and appreciate any donations of water that parents want to contribute. Thanks in advance if you are able.

post_text:
Football Fans traveling to Broadus on Friday, August 28th.

Varsity will be kicking off at 7:00pm.

Broadus is NOT limiting fans at this football game due to plenty of room to social distance. Fans will be allowed to stand and spread out all around the track.
They will taking temperatures of all fans before entrance into their facility. Anyone with 100.4 or higher temperature will NOT be admitted.
Masks are not being required at this time for fans, but it would be a good idea to bring one in case something changes at the last minute.

Safe travels and good luck, Wildcats!

SPORTS PHYSICAL 2020-2021
- SMH will not be coming to the school to perform physicals due to Covid and social distancing
- Students/Parents will be required to call SMH Clinic to schedule an appointment
- $20 sports physical
- Day and times physicals will be offered: August 5 from 9-1 and 1-5.
- Students pick up sports physical forms at the school
- Make sure to have form filled out and signed by parent prior to presenting for appointment and the $20 is also due at time of visit
- Please start making appointments ASAP as slots will fill fast
- Students that have underlying chronic medical conditions are asked to please schedule their sports physical with their regular provider on a different date
PLEASE MAKE SURE YOU TURN YOUR PHYSICAL INTO THE SCHOOL OFFICE. YOU WILL NOT BE ABLE TO PRACTICE WITHOUT THE FORM PRESENT AT THE SCHOOL.YOU CAN DROP YOUR FORM OFF DURING SUMMER HOURS AT THE SCHOOL.

Montana Farm to School
July 9 at 11:02 AM ¬∑

First Lady Lisa Bullock recently announced the 2020 recipients of the ‚ÄúFirst Lady School Nutrition Awards.‚Äù This honor is given to Montana schools that encourage success for all students through the initiation and continued support of school nutrition programs.

‚ÄúMontana‚Äôs kids need nutritious meals to thrive inside and outside of the classroom,‚Äù First Lady Bullock said. ‚ÄúThese schools have excelled at developing programs that remove nutritional barriers so their students can succeed. I thank them for partnering with us as we strive to eliminate childhood hunger in Montana.‚Äù

2020 First Lady School Nutrition Award Recipients:

School Breakfast Champion Award - Ridge View Elementary, Belgrade
Wholesome School Menu Award - Huntley Project Schools
School Nutrition Innovation Award - Plentywood School District
Honorable Mentions- St. Labre Schools, Evergreen Jr. High School, Livingston School District and Farm to School Park County, Forsyth High School
School Nutrition Team of the Year - William Harvey, Ronan
Honorable Mention - Ennis K-12 Schools

Congratulations, honorees!

Here is a how to list for people to watch graduation if they have never watched on Nemont.TV. We have made up a generic username/password for everyone to use so they don‚Äôt have to Sign up.

1. Go to www.nemont.tv
2. Left of the search box, click Login
3. Username/email: nemt2020
Password: nemt2020
4. Click the Watch Now box below Grad 2020
5. Click the frozen video or paused video and the video should play.

People should be seeing a ‚ÄúComing up Next Graduation‚Äù video that loops about 10-15 minutes before the graduation starts. When we get to about 5 minutes before graduation, we will go LIVE to your school.

I recommend signing in an hour ahead to see if everything is working and just leave it on. If someone has an iPhone, we do have an app for it. If anyone misses the graduation we will be putting it up to watch On Demand on www.nemont.tv as well as our Nemont.TV Youtube page.

From Sheridan Memorial Hospital:

SPORTS PHYSICAL 2020-2021
- SMH will not be coming to the school to perform physicals due to Covid and social distancing
- Students/Parents will be required to call SMH Clinic to schedule an appointment
- $20 sports physical
- Day and times physicals will be offered, June 17, 24, July 8, 15, 22, 29, and August 5 from 9-1 and 1-5.
- Students pick up sports physical forms at the school
- Make sure to have form filled out and signed by parent prior to presenting for appointment and the $20 is also due at time of visit
- Please start making appointments ASAP as slots will fill fast
- Students that have underlying chronic medical conditions are asked to please schedule their sports physical with their regular provider on a different date

PLEASE MAKE SURE YOU TURN YOUR PHYSICAL INTO THE SCHOOL OFFICE. YOU WILL NOT BE ABLE TO PRACTICE WITHOUT THE FORM PRESENT AT THE SCHOOL.YOU CAN DROP YOUR FORM OFF DURING SUMMER HOURS AT THE SCHOOL.

This Friday, May 22nd will be the final drop off of learning materials including computers, textbooks, and any missing assignments. There will be no buckets outside. Please ring the doorbell to hand in and keep your social distance from the next person in line.
These are suggested times to turn in materials:
8:00 - 9:00 a.m. - KG-2
9:00 - 10:00 a.m. - Gr. 3-5
10:00 - 11:00 a.m. - Gr. 6-8
11:00 a.m. - 12:00 p.m. - Gr. 9-10
12:00 - 1:00 p.m. - Gr. 11-12
1:00 p.m. - 2:00 p.m. - items that may have been missed
Please make sure all materals are returned at this time! If the time suggested does not work with your work schedule, you can drop off at a time that does.

We request that rural students/parents drop off at the school on this day if at all possible so that all school owned textbooks and devices are returned safely. If it isn't possible, please let us know and we will have the bus stop and pick up on this day.

post_text:
Hello High School Students:

The 4th Quarter midterm grades were sent home last week. If you have yet to view this report, I highly recommend students (and parents) login into Infinite Campus for updated grades.

The final grades entered for the end of the 4th Quarter (May 29, 2020) will determine eligibility for Fall Co-Curricular Activities. Eligibility is based on a student earning a passing grade in ALL subjects at the end of each four and a half week grading period.A student who fails to earn a passing grade in all subjects will be ineligible for co-curricular activities for the entire next four and a half week grading period. Quarter and midterm grades will determine eligibility, not semester grades.

Make sure all of your assignments are submitted for EVERY class (including electives). Please continue to work on ALL assignments over the next three weeks. I am proud of all your work and dedication this past quarter. Keep up the great work! üò∫

Please contact your teachers if you have any questions/concerns on current grades or assignments.

Thank you,
Dr. Amanda L. Simonson

Between preparing healthy meals for America‚Äôs students, adhering to strict nutrition standards, navigating student food allergies, and offering service with a smile, school nutrition professionals are true heroes.

On Friday, May 1, 2020, we will celebrate the 8th Annual School Lunch Hero Day! School Lunch Hero Day is a chance to showcase the difference school nutrition professionals make for every child who comes through the cafeteria.

Thanks to Maria Schwarzrock, Jeanne Tange, Suzy Marsh, and Ruth Mehl for the awesome job they do each day for our students! Did you realize they served a total of 2,239 meals to our students in April with school closed??!!

They truly are Super Heroes to us!

post_text:
This comes from biglifejournal.com:

This unsettling time is such a great opportunity to build and model resilience for our children.
Here's one of my favorite activities for this:
Explain to your children that each one of us is like a tree. And the challenges we're facing are like the wind which bends the tree.
Trees stand strong despite the wind because of their strong root system (support system): family, friends, pets, their MINDSET, positive thoughts, beliefs, values, etc.
Trees need wind to blow against them because it helps their root systems to grow deeper, which supports the tree as it grows taller.
In other words, the tree welcomes the strong wind because it helps it grow STRONGER!
So similar in life, challenges make us stronger! Such experiences as we're facing these days develop our character and our mindset and deepen our roots.
When we grow deep, we too, stand tall!

All other students who would like a lunch may come to the school cafeteria door between 11:30 a.m. and 12:30 p.m. to have a ‚Äúgrab and go‚Äù lunch handed to you that you must take and consume without entering the building. Lunches will consist each day of a different type of sub sandwich, chips, fruit, and milk.

Please share your ideas for other weekly themes, I'd love to hear them!
